question:

Additionally, a randomized Phase II study (NCT00402051) compared Pemetrexed in combination with either Cisplatin or Carboplatin as first-line therapy for patients with locally advanced or metastatic non-small-cell lung cancer. These trials provide comprehensive insights into the efficacy of these treatment combinations for non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer.

question:

This Phase II MyeloMATCH treatment trial evaluates the standard approach of Cytarabine and Daunorubicin (7+3) against several experimental regimens in patients with high-risk Acute Myeloid Leukemia. The primary objective is to compare measurable residual disease (MRD) negative complete remission (CR) rates between each experimental regimen and the standard 7+3 regimen. Another relevant study is NCT03507842, a prospective randomized trial comparing high-dose Cytarabine plus Daunorubicin (HDAC) versus Cytarabine plus high-dose Daunorubicin (AD) in induction chemotherapy for Acute Myeloid Leukemia. The primary hypothesis is that the AD regimen is superior to HDAC in terms of event-free survival. ([ichgcp.net](https://ichgcp.net/clinical-trials-registry/NCT03507842?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, NCT00715637 is a Phase III open-label randomized study comparing Cytarabine in combination with Amonafide L-malate or Daunorubicin as induction therapy for patients with secondary Acute Myeloid Leukemia. The study concluded that induction treatment with Cytarabine and Amonafide did not improve the complete remission rate compared with Cytarabine and Daunorubicin in patients with secondary Acute Myeloid Leukemia. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25732165/?utm_source=openai))

These trials provide insights into the efficacy of Cytarabine and Daunorubicin regimens in treating Acute Myeloid Leukemia.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of Paclitaxel monotherapy compared to Buparlisib and Paclitaxel when used to treat Head and neck cancer.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of paclitaxel monotherapy compared to the combination of buparlisib and paclitaxel in treating head and neck cancer is identified by the ClinicalTrials.gov identifier NCT01852292. ([dana-farber.org](https://www.dana-farber.org/clinical-trials/13-461?utm_source=openai))

This Phase II, multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled study assessed the efficacy and safety of buparlisib (BKM120) plus paclitaxel versus placebo plus paclitaxel in patients with platinum-pretreated recurrent or metastatic head and neck squamous cell carcinoma. ([dana-farber.org](https://www.dana-farber.org/clinical-trials/13-461?utm_source=openai))

The primary endpoint was progression-free survival (PFS), and the key secondary endpoint was overall survival (OS). ([dana-farber.org](https://www.dana-farber.org/clinical-trials/13-461?utm_source=openai))

The study found that the combination of buparlisib and paclitaxel improved PFS compared to paclitaxel alone, with a median PFS of 4.6 months versus 3.5 months, respectively. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/abs/10.1200/JCO.2016.34.15_suppl.6008?utm_source=openai))

The safety profile of the combination was manageable, with the most common grade 3-4 adverse events being hyperglycemia, anemia, neutropenia, and fatigue. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/abs/10.1200/JCO.2016.34.15_suppl.6008?utm_source=openai))

These results suggest that buparlisib in combination with paclitaxel could be an effective second-line treatment for patients with platinum-pretreated recurrent or metastatic squamous cell carcinoma of the head and neck. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/abs/10.1200/JCO.2016.34.15_suppl.6008?utm_source=openai))

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of Carboplatin and Paclitaxel (CP) and Ipilimumab compared to Carboplatin and Paclitaxel (CP) when used to treat Non-small cell lung cancer.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of Carboplatin and Paclitaxel (CP) combined with Ipilimumab compared to CP alone in treating non-small cell lung cancer is identified by the ClinicalTrials.gov identifier NCT01285609. ([bmsclinicaltrials.com](https://www.bmsclinicaltrials.com/us/en/clinical-trials/NCT01285609?utm_source=openai))

This Phase 3, randomized, double-blind, multinational study evaluated whether adding Ipilimumab to the standard CP regimen could extend the lives of patients with Stage IV or recurrent non-small cell lung cancer of squamous histology. The trial has been completed, and results are available on ClinicalTrials.gov. ([bmsclinicaltrials.com](https://www.bmsclinicaltrials.com/us/en/clinical-trials/NCT01285609?utm_source=openai))

Another relevant study is NCT00527735, a Phase 2 trial that assessed the efficacy and safety of Ipilimumab in combination with Paclitaxel and Carboplatin compared to the chemotherapy regimen alone in previously untreated subjects with non-small cell lung cancer. This study has also been completed. ([ichgcp.net](https://ichgcp.net/clinical-trials-registry/NCT00527735?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, NCT02279732 is a Phase 3 trial that compared Ipilimumab plus Paclitaxel and Carboplatin versus placebo plus Paclitaxel and Carboplatin in subjects with squamous non-small cell lung cancer. This study aimed to determine whether the addition of Ipilimumab could extend the life of patients more than the standard chemotherapy regimen alone. The trial has been completed, and results are available on ClinicalTrials.gov. ([bmsclinicaltrials.com](https://www.bmsclinicaltrials.com/au/en/clinical-trials/NCT02279732?utm_source=openai))

These studies provide valuable insights into the potential benefits of incorporating Ipilimumab into standard chemotherapy regimens for treating non-small cell lung cancer.

question:

model_output:
I couldn't locate a clinical trial that directly compares the efficacy of fulvestrant (FULV) to hepatic arterial chemotherapy in the treatment of colorectal cancer. Fulvestrant is primarily used in the management of hormone receptor-positive breast cancer and is not a standard treatment for colorectal cancer.

However, there is a relevant clinical trial that evaluates hepatic arterial infusion (HAI) chemotherapy for unresectable colorectal cancer liver metastases. This randomized phase II trial compared HAI of oxaliplatin plus raltitrexed (TOMOX) versus oxaliplatin plus 5-fluorouracil (FOLFOX). question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of TX-CEX compared to D-FEC when used to treat Breast cancer.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of TX-CEX compared to T-CEF in treating early breast cancer is registered under the identifier NCT00114816. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28253390/?utm_source=openai))

In this randomized, open-label, multicenter trial, 1,500 patients with axillary node-positive or high-risk node-negative early breast cancer were assigned to receive either TX-CEX (docetaxel and capecitabine followed by cyclophosphamide, epirubicin, and capecitabine) or T-CEF (docetaxel followed by cyclophosphamide, epirubicin, and fluorouracil). The study aimed to evaluate recurrence-free survival (RFS) and overall survival (OS) between the two regimens.

The results indicated no significant difference in RFS or OS between the groups. However, exploratory analyses suggested that patients with triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC) might benefit more from the TX-CEX regimen, showing improved survival outcomes compared to T-CEF. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28253390/?utm_source=openai))

Therefore, NCT00114816 provides comprehensive data on the comparative efficacy of TX-CEX versus T-CEF in early breast cancer treatment.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of Cyclosporine, Methotrexate, ATG compared to Cyclosporine and Methotrexate when used to treat Graft versus host disease.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
I couldn't locate a clinical trial with an NCT number that directly compares the efficacy of Cyclosporine, Methotrexate, and Antithymocyte Globulin (ATG) versus Cyclosporine and Methotrexate in treating Graft-versus-Host Disease (GVHD). However, several studies have evaluated similar combinations:

- **Cyclosporine and Methotrexate vs. Cyclosporine Alone**: A study published in the *New England Journal of Medicine* compared these regimens for GVHD prophylaxis in leukemia patients undergoing marrow transplantation. The combination of Methotrexate and Cyclosporine significantly reduced the incidence of acute GVHD compared to Cyclosporine alone. ([nejm.org](https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejm198603203141201?utm_source=openai))

([ashpublications.org](https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/96/7/2391/181059/Cyclosporine-methotrexate-and-methylprednisolone?utm_source=openai))

While these studies do not include ATG, they provide insights into the efficacy of various combinations in GVHD prophylaxis. For the most current and specific clinical trials, I recommend searching the [ClinicalTrials.gov](https://clinicaltrials.gov/) database using relevant keywords.

model_output:
I couldn't locate a clinical trial with an NCT number that directly compares the efficacy of the combination of mercaptopurine, methotrexate, vincristine, and dexamethasone to methotrexate and vincristine alone in treating pediatric B-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL). However, several studies have evaluated the effectiveness of these drug combinations in pediatric ALL treatment:

1. **Pediatric Oncology Group (POG) Phase III Trial**: This study compared intermediate-dose intravenous methotrexate with intravenous mercaptopurine to repetitive low-dose oral methotrexate with intravenous mercaptopurine in children with lower-risk B-lineage ALL. The results indicated that the intravenous regimen was more effective in preventing relapse. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/10.1200/JCO.1998.16.1.246?utm_source=openai))

The findings suggested that these interventions improved outcomes in the studied population. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4981974/?utm_source=openai))

3. **POG Phase III Randomized Trial**: This study evaluated early intensive methotrexate/mercaptopurine therapy compared to early intensive alternating combination chemotherapy in children with high-risk B-precursor ALL. The study found no significant difference in event-free survival between the two regimens, though the combination chemotherapy was more toxic. ([nature.com](https://www.nature.com/articles/2402132?utm_source=openai))

While these studies provide valuable insights into the use of these medications in pediatric ALL treatment, they do not specifically compare the four-drug combination (mercaptopurine, methotrexate, vincristine, dexamethasone) to the two-drug regimen (methotrexate and vincristine) in the context of pediatric B-cell ALL.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of VAD (Pegylated liposomal doxorubicin substituted) compared to VAD when used to treat Multiple myeloma.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of pegylated liposomal doxorubicin (PLD) compared to conventional doxorubicin in the treatment of multiple myeloma is registered under the identifier NCT00344422. This Phase III multicenter randomized trial compared the combination of PLD, vincristine, and dexamethasone (DVd) with the traditional regimen of doxorubicin, vincristine, and dexamethasone (VAd) in patients with newly diagnosed multiple myeloma. ([ichgcp.net](https://ichgcp.net/clinical-trials-registry/NCT00344422?utm_source=openai))

The study found that both treatment groups had similar objective response rates (DVd: 44%; VAd: 41%), progression-free survival, and overall survival. However, the DVd regimen was associated with significantly reduced toxicity, including lower incidences of Grade 3/4 neutropenia or neutropenic fever (10% vs. 24%; P = 0.01), sepsis, and antibiotic use. Additionally, DVd resulted in less alopecia (20% vs. 44%; P < 0.001) but a higher occurrence of hand-foot syndrome (25% vs. 1%; P < 0.001), primarily Grade 1/2. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16404741/?utm_source=openai))

These findings suggest that substituting pegylated liposomal doxorubicin for conventional doxorubicin in the VAd regimen offers similar efficacy with a significant reduction in toxicity for patients with newly diagnosed multiple myeloma.

1. **Children's Cancer Group Phase III Trial**: This randomized trial compared MOPP/ABVD chemotherapy with ABVD plus low-dose extended-field radiation therapy in children and adolescents with advanced Hodgkin's disease. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/2033427/?utm_source=openai))

3. **Alternating MOPP and ABVD Chemotherapy Plus Radiation Therapy**: This study evaluated the efficacy of alternating MOPP and ABVD chemotherapy followed by mantle-field radiation therapy in patients with massive mediastinal Hodgkin's disease. The treatment regimen demonstrated high complete response rates and favorable long-term survival outcomes. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/9363863/?utm_source=openai))

While these studies provide insights into various treatment combinations involving MOPP-ABV and radiation therapy, none specifically address the direct comparison you're seeking. For more detailed information, you may refer to the provided studies.

This randomized Phase 3 study involved East Asian never-smoker or light ex-smoker patients with locally advanced or metastatic nonsquamous non-small cell lung cancer. Participants were assigned to receive either a combination of Pemetrexed and Cisplatin followed by maintenance therapy with Gefitinib, or Gefitinib monotherapy. The study aimed to compare the progression-free survival and overall survival between these two treatment approaches. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26725183/?utm_source=openai))

The results indicated that median overall survival was similar between the two groups: 26.9 months for the combination therapy group and 27.9 months for the monotherapy group. However, subgroup analyses revealed that patients with EGFR wild-type tumors had longer median overall survival with the combination therapy (28.4 months) compared to monotherapy (8.9 months). Conversely, patients with EGFR-mutated tumors experienced longer median overall survival with monotherapy (45.7 months) compared to the combination therapy (32.4 months). ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26725183/?utm_source=openai))

These findings underscore the importance of determining EGFR mutation status to select the most appropriate first-line treatment for patients with advanced non-small cell lung cancer.

([ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10419521/?utm_source=openai))

The SOFT trial evaluated the benefits of adding OFS to adjuvant endocrine therapy in premenopausal women with hormone receptor–positive breast cancer. It compared three treatment arms:

1. Tamoxifen alone
2. Tamoxifen plus OFS
3. Exemestane (an aromatase inhibitor similar to Letrozole) plus OFS

The 12-year results from SOFT indicated that the combination of an aromatase inhibitor with OFS provided a significant improvement in disease-free survival compared to Tamoxifen alone. ([ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10419521/?utm_source=openai))

While the SOFT trial specifically investigated Exemestane with OFS, its findings are often extrapolated to Letrozole due to their similar mechanisms of action as aromatase inhibitors. Therefore, NCT00066690 is the most relevant clinical trial for understanding the efficacy of Letrozole combined with OFS versus Tamoxifen with OFS in the treatment of breast cancer.

This randomized phase III study, conducted by the International Berlin-Frankfurt-Münster Study Group, found that adding liposomal daunorubicin (DNX) to the FLAG regimen improved early treatment response in pediatric relapsed AML. Specifically, the day 28 bone marrow status showed a good response (≤ 20% leukemic blasts) in 80% of patients treated with FLAG-DNX, compared to 70% in those treated with FLAG alone (P = .04). This Phase II randomized trial evaluates the efficacy of concurrent and adjuvant Pembrolizumab with RT versus RT plus Cisplatin in patients with intermediate/high-risk p16-positive locoregionally advanced head and neck squamous cell carcinoma (HNSCC). The primary endpoint is progression-free survival (PFS). ([ichgcp.net](https://ichgcp.net/clinical-trials-registry/NCT03383094?utm_source=openai))

Another relevant study is NCT03040999, a Phase III trial investigating Pembrolizumab or placebo administered concurrently with chemoradiation therapy (CRT) and as maintenance treatment in patients with locally advanced HNSCC. The primary hypothesis is that Pembrolizumab in combination with CRT is superior to placebo in combination with CRT with respect to event-free survival (EFS). ([clinicaltrials.ucsf.edu](https://clinicaltrials.ucsf.edu/trial/NCT03040999?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, NCT02777385 is a Phase II study evaluating concurrent or sequential fixed-dose Pembrolizumab in combination with Cisplatin and intensity-modulated radiotherapy (IMRT) in intermediate or high-risk, previously untreated, locally advanced head and neck cancer. The goal is to determine which therapy order may be more effective and to learn about the side effects of these combinations. ([trial.medpath.com](https://trial.medpath.com/clinical-trial/c4a165f5da80aa0d/nct02777385-randomized-study-pembrolizumab-cisplatin-radiotherapy-head-neck-cancer?utm_source=openai))

These trials aim to assess the efficacy and safety of combining Pembrolizumab with standard treatments for head and neck cancer.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA compared to R-CHOP when used to treat Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
I couldn't locate a clinical trial with an NCT number that directly compares the efficacy of R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA to R-CHOP in treating Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma (DLBCL). However, a prospective phase II study conducted by MD Anderson Cancer Center evaluated these regimens in patients aged ≤60 years with high-risk DLBCL. The study found that the complete response rate was higher with R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA compared to R-CHOP, leading to the closure of the R-CHOP arm. The 3-year progression-free survival rates were 75.7% for R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA and 77.8% for R-CHOP. Notably, in patients over 45 years old, R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA was associated with a 12% early mortality rate. ([mdanderson.elsevierpure.com](https://mdanderson.elsevierpure.com/en/publications/prospective-phase-ii-study-of-rituximab-with-alternating-cycles-o?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, a retrospective cohort study indicated that R-Hyper-CVAD/R-MA might overcome traditional poor risk features in high-risk DLBCL patients, suggesting its potential efficacy in this subgroup. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23488604/?utm_source=openai))

While these studies provide valuable insights, they do not correspond to a specific NCT-numbered clinical trial.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of Octreotide LAR monotherapy compared to Placebo when used to treat Pancreatic NET.

model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of Octreotide LAR monotherapy compared to placebo in treating pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors (NETs) is identified by the ClinicalTrials.gov identifier NCT00171873. This study, known as the PROMID trial, was a placebo-controlled, double-blind, prospective, randomized study focusing on the effect of Octreotide LAR in controlling tumor growth in patients with metastatic neuroendocrine midgut tumors. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19704057/?utm_source=openai))

The study found that Lanreotide significantly prolonged progression-free survival compared to placebo. ([nejm.org](https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmoa1316158?utm_source=openai))

While both trials provide valuable insights into the treatment of NETs with somatostatin analogs, specific data on Octreotide LAR monotherapy for pancreatic NETs may be limited.

These studies provide comprehensive insights into the efficacy of combining 5-FU with leucovorin and/or levamisole in the treatment of colorectal cancer.

question:
Find/search the clinical trial id that best describes the efficacy of TCH (Docetaxel) (trastuzumab-qyyp) compared to TCH (Docetaxel) when used to treat Breast cancer.
Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of TCH (docetaxel, carboplatin, and trastuzumab) compared to EC-TH (epirubicin, cyclophosphamide, followed by docetaxel and trastuzumab) in treating HER2-positive breast cancer is registered under the identifier NCT03140553. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/abs/10.1200/JCO.2020.38.15_suppl.585?utm_source=openai))

In this randomized, open-label, multicenter, phase II trial, 140 patients with stage II or III HER2-positive breast cancer were assigned to receive either the EC-TH regimen or the TCH regimen. The primary endpoint was the pathological complete response (pCR), defined as the absence of invasive tumor cells in both the breast and axilla (ypT0/is ypN0). The results indicated a pCR rate of 38.5% in the EC-TH group and 56.1% in the TCH group, with the difference being statistically significant (p=0.044). The incidence of adverse events was similar between the two groups, suggesting that the TCH regimen might be a preferred approach for neoadjuvant therapy in patients with HER2-positive breast cancer. ([ascopubs.org](https://ascopubs.org/doi/abs/10.1200/JCO.2020.38.15_suppl.585?utm_source=openai))

question:

The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of Carboplatin and Paclitaxel (CP) combined with Bevacizumab compared to CP alone in treating non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer is identified by the ClinicalTrials.gov number NCT00021060. ([nejm.org](https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmoa061884?utm_source=openai))

This randomized study, conducted by the Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG), evaluated 878 patients with recurrent or advanced non–small-cell lung cancer (stage IIIB or IV). Participants were assigned to receive either CP alone or CP plus Bevacizumab. The results demonstrated a significant survival benefit in the group receiving Bevacizumab, with a median survival of 12.3 months compared to 10.3 months in the chemotherapy-alone group. However, the addition of Bevacizumab was associated with an increased risk of treatment-related deaths. ([nejm.org](https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/nejmoa061884?utm_source=openai))

Regarding Bevacizumab-bvcr, a biosimilar to Bevacizumab, a relevant clinical trial is registered under ClinicalTrials.gov number NCT05654454. This randomized, double-blind, phase III trial compares the safety and efficacy of Bevacizumab (manufactured by Mabscale LLC) plus Paclitaxel and Carboplatin to Avastin® (the brand name for Bevacizumab) plus Paclitaxel and Carboplatin in patients with inoperable or advanced non-squamous non-small-cell lung cancer. The study aims to demonstrate the equivalence of efficacy and safety between the biosimilar Bevacizumab and Avastin®. ([ichgcp.net](https://ichgcp.net/clinical-trials-registry/NCT05654454?utm_source=openai))

Therefore, the clinical trial NCT05654454 best describes the efficacy of Carboplatin and Paclitaxel combined with Bevacizumab-bvcr compared to Carboplatin and Paclitaxel combined with Bevacizumab in treating non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer.

This Phase 2 study evaluates the activity of Trabectedin (Arm A) in advanced leiomyosarcomas, with Gemcitabine (Arm B) as the comparator. In addition to the randomized cohort, the study includes an observational prospective cohort for patients who refuse randomization or for whom randomization is deemed inappropriate by the investigator. The study aims to assess the efficacy of these treatments and includes an optional translational study to identify predictive factors for the activity of Trabectedin or Gemcitabine in this specific histotype.

Another relevant study is a randomized Phase II trial comparing letrozole to observation in patients with newly diagnosed early-stage uterine leiomyosarcoma. Although this study closed early due to low accrual, preliminary results suggested that aromatase inhibitor therapy might be an active agent in early-stage uterine leiomyosarcoma. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6260388/?utm_source=openai))

Additionally, a study analyzing data from the National Cancer Database examined the efficacy of adjuvant therapy versus observation in women with early-stage uterine-confined leiomyosarcoma. The findings indicated that the receipt of any adjuvant therapy had no significant effect on mortality compared to observation. ([pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7189070/?utm_source=openai))

These studies contribute to the understanding of the efficacy of observation compared to active treatments in managing leiomyosarcoma.

question:

Output it in the format NCT<Number>
model_output:
The clinical trial that best describes the efficacy of G-CSF monotherapy compared to the combination of Plerixafor and G-CSF in stem cell mobilization is registered under the identifier NCT00103662. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19363221/?utm_source=openai))

This Phase III, multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled study evaluated the safety and efficacy of Plerixafor with G-CSF in mobilizing hematopoietic stem cells in patients with multiple myeloma. Patients received G-CSF (10 μg/kg) subcutaneously daily for up to 8 days. Beginning on day 4 and continuing daily for up to 4 days, patients received either Plerixafor (240 μg/kg) or placebo subcutaneously. Starting on day 5, patients began daily apheresis for up to 4 days or until ≥6 × 10⁶ CD34⁺ cells/kg were collected. The primary endpoint was the percentage of patients who collected ≥6 × 10⁶ CD34⁺ cells/kg in ≤2 aphereses. A total of 71.6% of patients in the Plerixafor group and 34.4% of patients in the placebo group met the primary endpoint (P < .001). The most common adverse events related to Plerixafor were gastrointestinal disorders and injection site reactions. Plerixafor and G-CSF were well tolerated, and significantly more patients collected the optimal CD34⁺ cell/kg target for transplantation earlier compared with G-CSF alone. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19363221/?utm_source=openai))

These findings suggest that lapatinib, when added to letrozole, offers a significant benefit over letrozole alone in this patient population.
